	<H3 CLASS="center"><A ID="IV"></A>
IV
	<BR><SPAN CLASS="smaller">
Wild Sheep
	<BR><SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">
In ovifero (hoc est ovis silvatica)&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="IVref1" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#IVnote1
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">1</A>
	</SPAN></SPAN></H3>

	<H4 CLASS="start center"><A NAME="348"></A>
348 Sauce for Mountain Sheep<!-- original has a period here -->
	<BR><SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">
Ius in ovifero fervens
	</SPAN></H4>

	<P CLASS="justify">
<SPAN CLASS="outquote">That is, (roast the meat, prepare a sauce of</SPAN>&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" NAME="348ref1" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#348note1
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">1</A> pepper, lovage, cumin, dry mint,&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" NAME="348ref2" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#348note2
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">2</A> thyme, silphium, moisten with wine, add stewed Damascus prunes, honey, wine, broth, vinegar, raisin wine, — enough to color — and stir with a whip of origany and dry mint.&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" NAME="348ref3" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#348note3
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">3</A>
<DIV CLASS="prose">
	<P>
	<A CLASS="note" NAME="348note1" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#348ref1
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">1</A>
<SPAN CLASS="manuscript">G.‑V.</SPAN>, <SPAN CLASS="manuscript">List.</SPAN> <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">in ovi fero</SPAN>; <SPAN CLASS="manuscript">Dann.</SPAN> "wild eggs," <I>i.e.</I>, eggs of game birds, and he comes to the conclusion that game birds themselves are meant to be used in this formula, as no reference to "eggs" is made.
	<P CLASS="i1 b0 a0 justify">
There can be no doubt but what this formula deals with the preparation of sheep; Torinus says expressly: <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">oviferum, hoc est, carnem ovis sylvestris</SPAN> — the meat of sheep from the woods, mountain sheep. <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">Ferum</SPAN> is "wild," "game," but it also means "pregnant." For this double sense the formula may be interpreted as dealing with either wild sheep, or with pregnant sheep, or, more probably, with unborn baby lamb, which in antiquity as today is often killed principally for its skin.

	<P>
	<A CLASS="note" NAME="348note2" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#348ref2
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">2</A>
<SPAN CLASS="manuscript">Tor.</SPAN>

	<P>
	<A CLASS="note" NAME="348note3" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#348ref3
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">3</A>
Mint is still associated with lamb; the above sauce appears to be merely an elaborate Roman ancestor of our modern mint sauce, served with lamb, the chief ingredients of which are mint, vinegar and sugar, served both hot and cold.
</DIV>




	<H4 CLASS="start center"><A NAME="349"></A>
349 Sauce for all Kinds of Game, Boiled or Roast
	<BR><SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">
Ius in venationibus omnibus elixis et assis&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" NAME="349ref1" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#349note1
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">1</A>
	</SPAN></H4>

	<P CLASS="justify">
8 scruples of pepper, rue, lovage, celery seed, juniper, thyme, dry mint, 6 scruples in weight <SPAN CLASS="outquote">each</SPAN> 3 scruples of flea-bane; reduce all this to the finest powder, put it together in a vessel with sufficient honey and use it with vinegar and garum.

<DIV CLASS="prose">
	<P>
	<A CLASS="note" NAME="349note1" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#349ref1
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">1</A>
<SPAN CLASS="manuscript">Tor.</SPAN> <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">Jusculum Omni Venationi competens</SPAN>.
</DIV>




	<H4 CLASS="start center"><A NAME="350"></A>
350 Cold Sauce for Wild Sheep
	<BR><SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">
Ius frigidum in ovifero&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" NAME="350ref1" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#350note1
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">1</A>
	</SPAN></H4>

	<P CLASS="justify">
Pepper, lovage, thyme, cumin, crushed toasted


<A ID="p189"><SPAN CLASS="pagenum"> p189 </SPAN></A>nuts, honey, vinegar, broth, and oil; sprinkle with pepper.

<DIV CLASS="prose">
	<P>
	<A CLASS="note" NAME="350note1" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#350ref1
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">1</A>
<SPAN CLASS="manuscript">List.</SPAN> <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">Omni fero</SPAN>; which <SPAN CLASS="manuscript">Dann.</SPAN> interprets, "All kind of game." <I>Cf.</I> note 1 to ℞ No. 348</A>.
</DIV>




	<H3 CLASS="center"><A ID="V"></A>
V
	<BR><SPAN CLASS="smaller">
Beef or Veal
	<BR><SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">
Bubula sive vitellina
	</SPAN></SPAN></H3>

	<H4 CLASS="start center"><A NAME="351"></A>
351 Veal Steak
	<BR><SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">
Vitellina fricta&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" NAME="351ref1" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#351note1
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">1</A>
	</SPAN></H4>


	<P CLASS="justify">
<SPAN CLASS="outquote">For a sauce with fried beef or veal take</SPAN>&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" NAME="351ref2" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#351note2
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">2</A> pepper, lovage, celery seed, cumin, origany, dry onion, raisins, honey, vinegar, wine, broth, oil, and reduced must.

<DIV CLASS="prose">
	<P>
	<A CLASS="note" NAME="351note1" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#351ref1
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">1</A>
Evidently a beef or veal steak <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">sauté</SPAN>. Beef did not figure very heavily on the dietary of the ancients in <INS CLASS="slip"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(SourceErr+'contrasts</SPAN>')"
onMouseOut="nd();">contrast</INS> to present modes which make beef the most important meat, culinarily speaking. The above sauce, save for the raisins and honey, resembles the modern <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">Bordelaise</SPAN>, often served with beef steaks <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">sauté</SPAN>, in contrast to the grilled steaks which are served with <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">maître d'hôtel</SPAN> butter.
</DIV>




	<H4 CLASS="start center"><A NAME="352"></A>
352 Veal or Beef with Leeks
	<BR><SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">
Vitulinam&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" NAME="352ref1" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#352note1
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">1</A> sive <INS CLASS="slip"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(SourceErr+'bululam</SPAN>')"
onMouseOut="nd();">bubulam</INS> cum porris
	</SPAN></H4>

	<P CLASS="justify">
<SPAN CLASS="outquote">or</SPAN> with quinces&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" NAME="352ref2" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#352note2
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">2</A> or with onions, or with dasheens&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" NAME="352ref3" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#352note3
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">3</A> <SPAN CLASS="outquote">use</SPAN> broth, pepper, laser and a little oil.

<DIV CLASS="prose">
	<P>
	<A CLASS="note" NAME="352note1" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#352ref1
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">1</A>
<SPAN CLASS="manuscript">G.‑V.</SPAN> same as <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">vitellinam</SPAN>.

	<P>
	<A CLASS="note" NAME="352note2" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#352ref2
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">2</A>
<SPAN CLASS="manuscript">Tor.</SPAN> <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">Cydoniis</SPAN>; <SPAN CLASS="manuscript">List.</SPAN> <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">Succidaneis</SPAN>.

	<P>
	<A CLASS="note" NAME="352note3" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#352ref3
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">3</A>
<I>Cf.</I> ℞ No. 332
	</A> <I>et al.</I>
</DIV>




	<H4 CLASS="start center"><A NAME="353"></A>
353 Fricassée of Veal
	<BR><SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">
In vitulinam elixam
	</SPAN></H4>

	<P CLASS="justify">
Crush pepper, lovage, caraway, celery seed, moisten with honey, vinegar, broth and oil; heat, bind with roux and cover the meat.


	<H4 CLASS="start center"><A NAME="354"></A>
354 Another Veal Fricassée
	<BR><SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">
Aliter in vitulina elixa
	</SPAN></H4>

	<P CLASS="justify">
Pepper, lovage, fennel seed, origany, nuts, fig-dates, honey, vinegar, broth, mustard and oil.


	<H3 CLASS="center"><A ID="VI"></A>
VI
	<BR><SPAN CLASS="smaller">
Kid or Lamb
	<BR><SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">
In haedo vel agno
	</SPAN></SPAN></H3>

	<H4 CLASS="start center"><A NAME="355"></A>
355 Dainty dishes of kid or of lamb
	<BR><SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">
Copadia haedina sive agnina
	</SPAN></H4>

	<P CLASS="justify">
Cook with pepper and broth, also with various


<A ID="p190"><SPAN CLASS="pagenum"> p190 </SPAN></A>ordinary beans&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" NAME="355ref1" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#355note1
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">1</A> broth, pepper and laser, cumin, dumplings&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" NAME="355ref2" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#355note2
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">2</A> and a little oil.&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" NAME="355ref3" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#355note3
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">3</A>

<DIV CLASS="prose">
	<P>
	<A CLASS="note" NAME="355note1" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#355ref1
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">1</A>
<SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">cum faseolis</SPAN>, green string beans.

	<P>
	<A CLASS="note" NAME="355note2" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#355ref2
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">2</A>
<SPAN CLASS="manuscript">Tor.</SPAN> <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">imbrato</SPAN>; <SPAN CLASS="manuscript">G.‑V.</SPAN> <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">inbracto</SPAN>, broken bread, regular dumplings.

	<P>
	<A CLASS="note" NAME="355note3" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#355ref3
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">3</A>
Lamb and beans is a favorite combination, as in the French <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">haricot</SPAN>, made with white beans, or boiled lamb with fresh string beans, quite a modern dish. Torinus omits the cumin, which is quite characteristic.
</DIV>




	<H4 CLASS="start center"><A NAME="356"></A>
356 Another Lamb Stew
	<BR><SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">
Aliter haedinam sive agninam excaldatam
	</SPAN></H4>

	<P CLASS="justify">
Put <SPAN CLASS="outquote">pieces of</SPAN> kid or lamb in the stew pot with chopped onion and coriander. Crush pepper, lovage, cumin, and cook with broth oil and wine. Put in a dish and tie with roux.&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" NAME="356ref1" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#356note1
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">1</A>

<DIV CLASS="prose">
	<P>
	<A CLASS="note" NAME="356note1" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#356ref1
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">1</A>
It appears that the binding should be done before the stew is dished out; but this sentence illustrates the consummate art of Apicius. The good cook carefully separates the meat (as it is cooked) from the sauce, eliminates impurities, binds and strains it and puts the meat back into the finished sauce. This is the ideal way of making a stew which evidently was known to Apicius

</DIV>




	<H4 CLASS="start center"><A NAME="357"></A>
357 Another Lamb Stew
	<BR><SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">
Aliter haedinam sive agninam excaldatam
	</SPAN></H4>

	<P CLASS="justify">
Add to the parboiled meat the raw herbs that have been crushed in the mortar and cook it. Goat meat is cooked likewise.


	<H4 CLASS="start center"><A NAME="358"></A>
358 Broiled Kid or Lamb Steak
	<BR><SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">
Haedum sive agnum assum
	</SPAN></H4>

	<P CLASS="justify">
Kid after being cooked in broth and oil is sliced and marinated&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" NAME="358ref1" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#358note1
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">1</A> with crushed pepper, laser, broth and a little oil. It is then grilled on the broiler and served with gravy. Sprinkle with pepper and serve up.

<DIV CLASS="prose">
	<P>
	<A CLASS="note" NAME="358note1" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#358ref1
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">1</A>
The marinade was used to make the gravy.
</DIV>




	<H4 CLASS="start center"><A NAME="359"></A>
359 Roast Kid or Lamb
	<BR><SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">
Aliter haedum sive agnum assum
	</SPAN></H4>

	<P CLASS="justify">
<SPAN CLASS="outquote">Let us roast the kid or lamb, adding</SPAN>&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" NAME="359ref1" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#359note1
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">1</A> half an ounce of pepper, 6 scruples of foalbit&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" NAME="359ref2" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#359note2
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">2</A> a little


<A ID="p191"><SPAN CLASS="pagenum"> p191 </SPAN></A>ginger, 6 scruples of parsley, a little laser, a pint of best broth and a spoonful oil.&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" NAME="359ref3" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#359note3
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">3</A>

<DIV CLASS="prose">
	<P>
	<A CLASS="note" NAME="359note1" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#359ref1
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">1</A>
<SPAN CLASS="manuscript">Tor.</SPAN>

	<P>
	<A CLASS="note" NAME="359note2" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#359ref2
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">2</A>
<SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">Asarum</SPAN>; <SPAN CLASS="manuscript">Tor.</SPAN> <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">aseros</SPAN>; <SPAN CLASS="manuscript">List.</SPAN> <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">asareos</SPAN> — the herb foalbit, foalfoot, wild spikenard.

	<P>
	<A CLASS="note" NAME="359note3" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#359ref3
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">3</A>
<SPAN CLASS="manuscript">Tor.</SPAN> continues without interruption.
</DIV>




	<H4 CLASS="start center"><A NAME="360"></A>
360 Stuffed Boned Kind or Lamb
	<BR><SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">
Haedus sive agnus syringiatus&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" NAME="360ref1" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#360note1
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">1</A>
	</SPAN></H4>

	<P CLASS="justify">
Milk-fed&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" NAME="360ref2" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#360note2
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">2</A> kid or lamb is carefully boned through the throat so as to create a paunch or bag; the intestines are preserved whole in a manner that one can blow or inflate them at the head in order to expel the excrements at the other end; the body is washed carefully and is filled with a <SPAN CLASS="whole">liquid</SPAN> dressing. Thereupon tie it carefully at the shoulders, put it into the roasting pan, baste well. When done, boil the gravy with milk and pepper, previously crushed, and broth, reduced wine, a little reduced must and also oil; and to the boiling gravy add roux. To play safe put the roast in a netting, bag or little basket and carefully tie together, add a little salt to the boiling gravy. After this has boiled well three times, take the meat out, boil the broth over again <SPAN CLASS="outquote">to reduce it</SPAN> incorporate with the above described liquor, adding the necessary seasoning.&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" NAME="360ref3" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#360note3
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">3</A><A CLASS="correction"
onMouseOver="return Ebox('The Dover edition<BR>omits the note marker',WIDTH,120)"
onMouseOut="nd();">º</A>

<DIV CLASS="prose">
	<P>
	<A CLASS="note" NAME="360note1" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#360ref1
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">1</A>
"Hollowed out like a pipe."

	<P>
	<A CLASS="note" NAME="360note2" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#360ref2
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">2</A>
<SPAN CLASS="manuscript">G.‑V.</SPAN> <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">syringiatus (id est mammotestus)</SPAN>. <SPAN CLASS="manuscript">Tor.</SPAN> <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">mammocestis</SPAN>. We are guessing.

	<P>
	<A CLASS="note" NAME="360note3" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#360ref3
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">3</A>
We would call this a Galatine<!-- sic --> of lamb if such a dish were made of lamb today.
	<P CLASS="i1 b0 a0 justify">
This article, like the following appears to be a contraction of two different formulae.
</DIV>




	<H4 CLASS="start center"><A NAME="361"></A>
361 Stuffed Kid or Lamb Another Way
	<BR><SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">
Aliter haedus sive agnus syringiatus
	</SPAN></H4>

	<P CLASS="justify">
Kid or lamb is thus prepared and seasoned: take&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" NAME="361ref1" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#361note1
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">1</A> 1 pint milk, 4 ounces honey, 1 ounce pepper, a little salt, a little laser, gravy <SPAN CLASS="outquote">of the lamb,</SPAN> 8 ounces crushed dates, a spoonful oil, a little broth, a


<A ID="p192"><SPAN CLASS="pagenum"> p192 </SPAN></A>spoonful honey&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" NAME="361ref2" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#361note2
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">2</A> a pint of good wine and a little roux.

<DIV CLASS="prose">
	<P>
	<A CLASS="note" NAME="361note1" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#361ref1
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">1</A>
<SPAN CLASS="manuscript">Tor.</SPAN>

	<P>
	<A CLASS="note" NAME="361note2" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#361ref2
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">2</A>
<SPAN CLASS="manuscript">G.‑V.</SPAN>
</DIV>




	<H4 CLASS="start center"><A NAME="362"></A>
362 The Raw Kid or Lamb&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" NAME="362ref1" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#362note1
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">1</A>
	<BR><SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">
Haedus sive agnus crudus
	</SPAN></H4>

	<P CLASS="justify">
Is rubbed with oil and pepper and sprinkled with plenty of clean salt and coriander seed, placed in the oven, served roast.

<DIV CLASS="prose">
	<P>
	<A CLASS="note" NAME="362note1" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#362ref1
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">1</A>
It is quite evident that this sentence belongs to the preceding formula; but all the texts make a distinct separation.
</DIV>




	<H4 CLASS="start center"><A NAME="363"></A>
363 Kid or Lamb à la Tarpeius&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" NAME="363ref1" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#363note1
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">1</A>
	<BR><SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">
Haedus sive agnum Tarpeianum
	</SPAN></H4>

	<P CLASS="justify">
Before cooking the lamb truss it properly and <SPAN CLASS="outquote">marinate it in</SPAN> pepper, rue, satury, onions, and a little thyme and broth. Place the roast in a pan with oil, baste well while in the oven, when cooked thoroughly, fill the pan with crushed satury, onions, rue, dates, broth, wine, reduced wine, and oil; when this gravy is well cooked <SPAN CLASS="outquote">strain</SPAN> put it up in a dish, sprinkle with pepper and serve.

<DIV CLASS="prose">
	<P>
	<A CLASS="note" NAME="363note1" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#363ref1
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">1</A>
<SPAN CLASS="manuscript">Tor.</SPAN> <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">Tatarpeianum</SPAN>.<A CLASS="comment"
onMouseOver="return Ebox('(sic)',WIDTH,60)"
onMouseOut="nd();">º</A> Tarpeius, family name of Romans. Humelberg thinks this dish is named for the people who dwelled on Mount Tarpeius. This was the Tarpeian Rock from which malefactors were thrown.

	<DIV CLASS="mynote">
		<P CLASS="b0 a0 justify">
Thayer's Note: There was, once, a <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">gens Tarpeia</SPAN>: it is very unlikely to have survived to a time such that it would have given its name to this recipe. "Mount Tarpeius" — Latin <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">Tarpeius mons</SPAN> — a topographical feature in the city of Rome, is usually rendered in English as "Tarpeian Rock"; its site is not certainly known, but the term probably refers to an outcrop of the more cliff-like southwestern area of the Capitoline Hill; for its location, see the references in the article
		<A CLASS="smallcaps" HREF="
E/Gazetteer/Places/Europe/Italy/Lazio/Roma/Rome/_Texts/PLATOP*/Tarpeius_Mons.html
		"TARGET="princeps"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,1,WIDTH,165)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Tarpeius Mons
		</A>
of Platner and Ashby's <I>Topographical Dictionary of Ancient Rome</I>.
		<P CLASS="i1 b0 a0 justify">
Whether people lived on the Tarpeian Rock is even more problematic; see the same dictionary's article
		<A CLASS="smallcaps" HREF="
E/Gazetteer/Places/Europe/Italy/Lazio/Roma/Rome/_Texts/PLATOP*/Capitolinus.html
		"TARGET="princeps"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,1,WIDTH,165)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Capitolinus</A>.
	</DIV>

</DIV>



	<H4 CLASS="start center"><A NAME="364"></A>
364 Kid or Lamb Parthian Style
	<BR><SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">
Haedus sive agnum Parthicum
	</SPAN></H4>

	<P CLASS="justify">
Put <SPAN CLASS="outquote">the roast</SPAN> in the oven; crush pepper, rue, onion, satury, stoned Damascus plums, a little laser, wine, broth and oil. Hot wine is served on the side and taken with vinegar.


	<H4 CLASS="start center"><A NAME="365"></A>
365 Creamed Kid Flavored with Laurel&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" NAME="365ref1" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#365note1
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">1</A>
	<BR><SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">
Haedum laureatum ex lacte
	</SPAN></H4>

	<P CLASS="justify">
<SPAN CLASS="outquote">The kid</SPAN> dress and prepare, bone, remove the intestines with the rennet and wash. Put in the mortar pepper, lovage, laser root, 2 laurel berries, a little chamomile and 2 or 3 brains, all of which crush. Moisten with broth and season


<A ID="p193"><SPAN CLASS="pagenum"> p193 </SPAN></A>with salt. Over this mixture strain 2 pints&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" NAME="365ref2" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#365note2
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">2</A> of milk, 2 little spoons of honey. With this forcemeat stuff the intestines and wrap them around the kid. Cover the roast with caul and parchment paper tightened with skewers, and place it in the roasting pan, adding broth, oil and wine. When half done, crush pepper, lovage, moisten with the roast's own gravy and a little reduced must; put this back into the pan and when the roast id done completely garnish it and bind <SPAN CLASS="outquote">the gravy</SPAN> with roux and serve.

<DIV CLASS="prose">
	<P CLASS="a0">
	<A CLASS="note" NAME="365note1" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#365ref1
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">1</A>
<SPAN CLASS="manuscript">Dan.</SPAN> thinks <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">laureatus</SPAN> stands for the best, the prize-winning meat, but the laurel may refer to the flavor used.
	<P CLASS="i1 b0 a0">
<SPAN CLASS="manuscript">List.</SPAN> remarks that cow's milk was very scarce in Italy; likewise was goat's and sheep's milk; hence it is possible that the kid was cooked with <INS CLASS="slip"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(SourceErr+'it\'s</SPAN>')"
onMouseOut="nd();">its</INS> mother's own milk.

	<P>
	<A CLASS="note" NAME="365note2" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#365ref2
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">2</A>
pints — <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">Sextarii</SPAN>.
</DIV>




	<H3 CLASS="center"><A ID="VII"></A>
VII
	<BR><SPAN CLASS="smaller">
Pig
	<BR><SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">
In porcello
	</SPAN></SPAN></H3>

	<H4 CLASS="start center"><A NAME="366"></A>
366 Suckling Pig Stuffed Two Ways
	<BR><SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">
Porcellum farsilem duobus generibus
	</SPAN></H4>

	<P CLASS="justify">
Prepare, remove the entrails by the throat before the carcass hardens <SPAN CLASS="outquote">immediately after killing</SPAN>. Make an opening under the ear, fill an ox bladder with Tarentine&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" NAME="366ref1" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#366note1
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">1</A> sausage meat and attach a tube such as the bird keeper uses to the neck of the bladder and squeeze the dressing into the ear as much as it will take to fill the body. Then seal the opening with parchment, close securely <SPAN CLASS="outquote">with skewers</SPAN> and prepare <SPAN CLASS="outquote">the roast for the oven</SPAN>.

<DIV CLASS="prose">
	<P>
	<A CLASS="note" NAME="366note1" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#366ref1
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">1</A>
<SPAN CLASS="manuscript">Tor.</SPAN> <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">impensam Tarentinam</SPAN>; <SPAN CLASS="manuscript">G.‑V.</SPAN> <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">Terentinam</SPAN>.

	<P CLASS="i1 b0 a0 justify">
The birdkeeper's tube may be an instrument for the cramming of fowl.
</DIV>




	<H4 CLASS="start center"><A NAME="366A"></A>
366a The other Dressing is made thus:
	<BR><SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">
zzz
	</SPAN></H4>

	<P CLASS="justify">
Crush pepper, lovage, origany, laser root, moisten with a little broth, add cooked brains, raw eggs, cooked spelt, gravy of the pig, small birds (if any) nuts, whole pepper, and season with broth. Stuff the pig, close the opening with parchment and skewers and put it in the oven. When done,


<A ID="p194"><SPAN CLASS="pagenum"> p194 </SPAN></A>dress and garnish very nicely, glaze the body and serve.


	<H4 CLASS="start center"><A NAME="367"></A>
367 Another Suckling Pig
	<BR><SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">
Aliter porcellum
	</SPAN></H4>

	<P CLASS="justify">
Salt, cumin, laser; add sausage meat. Dilute with broth&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" NAME="367ref1" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#367note1
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">1</A> remove the womb of the pig so that no part of it remains inside. Crush pepper, lovage, origany, moisten with broth, add wine&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" NAME="367ref2" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#367note2
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">2</A> brains, mix in 2 eggs, fill the <SPAN CLASS="outquote">previously</SPAN> parboiled pig with this forcemeat, close tight, place in a basket and immerse in the boiling stock pot. When done remove the skewers but in a manner that the gravy remains inside. Sprinkle with pepper, serve.

<DIV CLASS="prose">
	<P>
	<A CLASS="note" NAME="367note1" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#367ref1
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">1</A>
<SPAN CLASS="manuscript">G.‑V.</SPAN> treats the following as a separate article under the heading of <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">porcellum liquaminatum</SPAN>.

	<P>
	<A CLASS="note" NAME="367note2" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#367ref2
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">2</A>
<SPAN CLASS="manuscript">G.‑V.</SPAN> <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">unum</SPAN> (one brain) instead of <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">uinum</SPAN>.
</DIV>




	<H4 CLASS="start center"><A NAME="368"></A>
368 Stuffed Boiled Suckling Pig
	<BR><SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">
Porcellum elixum farsilem
	</SPAN></H4>

	<P CLASS="justify">
Remove the womb of the pig. Parboil. Crush pepper, lovage, origany, moisten with broth. Add cooked brains, as much as is needed&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" NAME="368ref1" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#368note1
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">1</A> likewise dissolve eggs, <SPAN CLASS="outquote">add</SPAN> broth to taste, make a sausage <SPAN CLASS="outquote">of this forcemeat</SPAN> fill the pig which has been parboiled and rinsed with broth. Tie the pig securely in a basket, immerse in the boiling stock pot. Remove when done, wipe clean carefully, serve without pepper.

<DIV CLASS="prose">
	<P>
	<A CLASS="note" NAME="368note1" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#368ref1
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">1</A>
To have a forcemeat of the right consistency.
</DIV>




	<H4 CLASS="start center"><A NAME="369"></A>
369 Roast Suckling Pig with Honey
	<BR><SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">
Porcellum assum tractomelinum&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" NAME="369ref1" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#369note1
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">1</A>
	</SPAN></H4>

	<P CLASS="justify">
Empty the pig by the neck, clean and dry, crush one ounce pepper, honey and wine, place <SPAN CLASS="outquote">this in a sauce pan and</SPAN> heat; next break dry toast&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" NAME="369ref2" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#369note2
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">2</A> and mix with the things in the sauce pan; stir with a whip of fresh laurel twigs&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" NAME="369ref3" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#369note3
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">3</A> so that the paste is nice and smooth until sufficiently cooked. This dressing fill into the pig, wrap in parchment, place in the oven <SPAN CLASS="outquote">roast slowly, when done, glaze with honey</SPAN> garnish nicely and serve.

<DIV CLASS="prose">
	<P>
	<A CLASS="note" NAME="369note1" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#369ref1
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">1</A>
treated with honey.

	<P>
	<A CLASS="note" NAME="369note2" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#369ref2
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">2</A>
<SPAN CLASS="manuscript">Tor.</SPAN> <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">tactam siccatam</SPAN> for <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">tractam</SPAN>.

	<P>
	<A CLASS="note" NAME="369note3" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#369ref3
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">3</A>
Again this very subtle method of flavoring, so often referred to. This time it is a laurel whip. <I>Cf.</I> ℞ Nos. 277 <I>seq.</I></A>,
345</A>,
369</A>,
385</A>.
</DIV>




	<H4 CLASS="start center"><A NAME="370"></A>
370 Milk-fed Pig, Cold, Apician Sauce
	<BR><SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">
Porcellum lacte pastum elixum calidum iure frigido crudo Apiciano
	</SPAN></H4>

	<P CLASS="justify">
Serve boiled milk-fed pig either hot or cold with this sauce&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" NAME="370ref1" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#370note1
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">1</A> in a mortar put pepper, lovage, coriander seed, mint, rue, and crush it. Moisten with broth. Add honey, wine and broth. The boiled pig is wiped off hot with a clean towel, <SPAN CLASS="outquote">cooled off</SPAN> covered with the sauce and served.&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" NAME="370ref2" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#370note2
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">2</A>

<DIV CLASS="prose">
	<P>
	<A CLASS="note" NAME="370note1" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#370ref1
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">1</A>
<SPAN CLASS="manuscript">Tor.</SPAN>

	<P>
	<A CLASS="note" NAME="370note2" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#370ref2
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">2</A>
This sentence wanting in <SPAN CLASS="manuscript">Tor.</SPAN>
</DIV>




	<H4 CLASS="start center"><A NAME="371"></A>
371 Suckling Pig à la Vitellius&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" NAME="371ref1" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#371note1
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">1</A>
	<BR><SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">
Porcellum Vitellianum
	</SPAN></H4>

	<P CLASS="justify">
Suckling pig called Vitellian style is prepared thus<SPAN CLASS="emend">:</SPAN>&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" NAME="371ref2" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#371note2
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">2</A> garnish the pig like wild boar&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" NAME="371ref3" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#371note3
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">3</A> sprinkle with salt, roast in oven. In the mortar put pepper, lovage, moisten with broth, wine and raisin wine to taste, put this in a sauce pan, adding very little oil, heat; the roasting pig baste with this in a manner so that <SPAN CLASS="outquote">the aroma</SPAN> will penetrate the skin.

<DIV CLASS="prose">
	<P>
	<A CLASS="note" NAME="371note1" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#371ref1
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">1</A>
Named for Vitellius, Roman emperor.

	<P>
	<A CLASS="note" NAME="371note2" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#371ref2
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">2</A>
<SPAN CLASS="manuscript">Tor.</SPAN> sentence wanting in other texts.

	<P>
	<A CLASS="note" NAME="371note3" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#371ref3
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">3</A>
<I>i.e.</I> marinated with raw vegetables, wine, spices, etc. <I>Cf.</I> ℞ Nos. 329‑30</A>.
</DIV>




	<H4 CLASS="start center"><A NAME="372"></A>
372 Suckling Pig à la Flaccus
	<BR><SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">
Porcellum Flaccianum&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" NAME="372ref1" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#372note1
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">1</A>
	</SPAN></H4>

	<P CLASS="justify">
The pig is garnished like wild boar.&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" NAME="372ref2" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#372note2
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">2</A> Sprinkle with salt, place in the oven. While being done put in the mortar pepper, lovage, caraway, celery seed, laser root, green rue, and crush it, moisten with broth, wine and raisin wine to taste, put this in a sauce pan, adding a little oil, heat, bind with roux. The roast pig, free from bones, sprinkle with powdered celery seed and serve.

<DIV CLASS="prose">
	<P>
	<A CLASS="note" NAME="372note1" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#372ref1
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">1</A>
<SPAN CLASS="manuscript">List.</SPAN> named for Flaccus Hordeonius, (<SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">puto</SPAN>). Flaccus was a rather common Roman family name.

	<P>
	<A CLASS="note" NAME="372note2" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#372ref2
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">2</A>
<I>Cf.</I> note 3 to ℞ No. 371 <!-- DON'T LINK -->, also ℞ Nos. 329‑30</A>. Lister is thoroughly puzzled by this procedure, but the problem is very simple: just treat the pig like wild boar.
</DIV>




	<H4 CLASS="start center"><A NAME="373"></A>
373 Suckling Pig, Laurel Flavor
	<BR><SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">
Porcellum laureatum
	</SPAN></H4>

	<P CLASS="justify">
The pig is boned and garnished with a little wine sauce&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" NAME="373ref1" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#373note1
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">1</A> parboil with green laurel in the center&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" NAME="373ref2" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#373note2
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">2</A> and place it in the oven to be roasted sufficiently. Meanwhile put in the mortar pepper, lovage, caraway, celery seed, laser root, and laurel berries, crush them, moisten with broth, wine and raisin wine to taste. <SPAN CLASS="outquote">Put this in a sauce pan and heat</SPAN> bind <SPAN CLASS="outquote">with roux; untie the pig</SPAN> remove the laurel leaves; incorporate the juice of the bones <SPAN CLASS="outquote">from which a gravy has been made in the meantime</SPAN> and serve.

<DIV CLASS="prose">
	<P>
	<A CLASS="note" NAME="373note1" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#373ref1
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">1</A>
Marinate<!-- printed text has lowercase --> in the ordinary way with <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">oenogarum</SPAN> as the dominant flavor.

	<P>
	<A CLASS="note" NAME="373note2" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#373ref2
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">2</A>
It is presumed that the boned pig is rolled and tied, with the leaves in the center.
</DIV>




	<H4 CLASS="start center"><A NAME="374"></A>
374 Suckling Pig à la Fronto&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" NAME="374ref1" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#374note1
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">1</A>
	<BR><SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">
Porcellum Frontinianum
	</SPAN></H4>

	<P CLASS="justify">
Bone the pig, parboil, garnish; in a sauce pan. Add broth, wine, bind. When half done, add a bunch of leeks and dill, some reduced must. When cooked wipe the pig clean, let it drip off; sprinkle with pepper, serve.

<DIV CLASS="prose">
	<P>
	<A CLASS="note" NAME="374note1" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#374ref1
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">1</A>
<SPAN CLASS="manuscript">List.</SPAN> Probably named for Julius Fronto, <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">praetor urbanus</SPAN> under Vitellius. Cornelius Fronto was an orator and author at the time of emperor Hadrian. <I>Cf.</I> ℞ No. 246</A>. <SPAN CLASS="manuscript">G.‑V.</SPAN> Frontinianus.
</DIV>




	<H4 CLASS="start center"><A NAME="375"></A>
375 Suckling Pig Stewed in Wine
	<BR><SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">
Porcellum Oenococtum&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" NAME="375ref1" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#375note1
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">1</A>
	</SPAN></H4>

	<P CLASS="justify">
Scald <SPAN CLASS="outquote">[parboil]</SPAN> the pig <SPAN CLASS="outquote">and</SPAN> marinate,&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" NAME="375ref2" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#375note2
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">2</A> place in a sauce pan <SPAN CLASS="outquote">with</SPAN> oil, broth, wine and water, tie a bunch of leeks and coriander; <SPAN CLASS="outquote">cook (in the oven)</SPAN> when half done color with reduced must. In the mortar put pepper, lovage, caraway, origany, celery seed, laser root and crush them, moisten with broth, add the pig's own gravy and raisin wine to taste. Add this <SPAN CLASS="outquote">to the meat in the sauce pan</SPAN> and


<A ID="p197"><SPAN CLASS="pagenum"> p197 </SPAN></A>let it boil. When boiling bind with roux. The pig, placed on a platter, mask <SPAN CLASS="outquote">with the sauce</SPAN> sprinkle with pepper and serve.

<DIV CLASS="prose">
	<P>
	<A CLASS="note" NAME="375note1" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#375ref1
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">1</A>
<SPAN CLASS="manuscript">Tor.</SPAN> <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">vino elixatus</SPAN>; <SPAN CLASS="manuscript">G.‑V.</SPAN> <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">aenococtum</SPAN>.

	<P>
	<A CLASS="note" NAME="375note2" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#375ref2
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">2</A>
It is presumed that the pig is prepared for coction as in the foregoing, namely cleaned, washed, boned, etc. This also applies to the succeeding recipes of pig.
</DIV>




	<H4 CLASS="start center"><A NAME="376"></A>
376 Pig à la Celsinus&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" NAME="376ref1" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#376note1
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">1</A>
	<BR><SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">
Porcellum Celsinianum
	</SPAN></H4>

	<P CLASS="justify">
Prepare <SPAN CLASS="outquote">as above</SPAN> inject <SPAN CLASS="outquote">the following dressing made of</SPAN> pepper, rue, onions, satury, the pig's own gravy <SPAN CLASS="outquote">and</SPAN> eggs through the ear&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" NAME="376ref2" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#376note2
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">2</A> and of pepper, broth and a little wine <SPAN CLASS="outquote">make a sauce which is served</SPAN> in the sauce boat;&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" NAME="376ref3" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#376note3
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">3</A> and enjoy it.

<DIV CLASS="prose">
	<P>
	<A CLASS="note" NAME="376note1" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#376ref1
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">1</A>
<SPAN CLASS="manuscript">Tor.</SPAN> <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">Caesianus</SPAN>; <SPAN CLASS="manuscript">Tac.</SPAN> <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">cesinianum</SPAN>; <SPAN CLASS="manuscript">G.‑V.</SPAN> <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">Celsinianum</SPAN>. Lister goes far out of his way to prove that the man for whom this dish was named was Celsinus. He cites a very amusing bit of ancient humor by Petrus Lambecius, given below.

	<P>
	<A CLASS="note" NAME="376note2" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#376ref2
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">2</A>
Really a dressing in a <SPAN CLASS="whole">liquid</SPAN> state when raw, a custard syringed into the carcass, which congeals during coction. Eggs must be in proper proportion to the other liquids. The pig thus filled is either steamed, roasted or baked, well protected by buttered or oiled paper — all of which the ancient author failed to state, as a matter of course.

	<P>
	<A CLASS="note" NAME="376note3" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#376ref3
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">3</A>
<SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">acetabulum</SPAN>.

<!-- BAD FORMATTING -->
"The Porker's Last Will and Testimony"
by Petrus Lambecius
(V. Barnab. Brissonium de Formulis lib. <SPAN CLASS="small">VII</SPAN>, p677)
[ex Lister, 1705, p196; Lister, 1709, p236].

"I, M. Grunter Corocotta Porker, do hereby make my last will and testament. Incapable of writing in my own hand, I have dictated what is to be set down:
"The Chief Cook sayeth: 'Come here, you — who has upset this house, you nuissance,<A CLASS="comment"
onMouseOver="return Ebox('(sic)',WIDTH,60)"
onMouseOut="nd();">º</A> you porker! I'll deprive you of your life this day!'
"Corocotta Porker sayeth: 'What, perchance, have I done? In what way, please, have I sinned? Have I with my feet perhaps smashed your crockery? I beg of you, Mr. Cook, I entreat you, if such be the case, kindly grant the supplicant a reprieve.'
"The Chief Cook sayeth: 'Go over there, boy! Fetch me from the kitchen that slaughtering-knife. I'm just itching to give this porker a blood-bath!'
"Mr. Porker, realizing that this is the season when cabbage sprouts are abundant, and visualizing himself potted and peppered, and furthermore seeing that death is inevitable, asks for time and begs of the cook whether it was possible to make a will. This granted, he calls out with a loud voice to his parents to save for them the food that was to have been his own in the future, to wit:
"To my father, Mr. Genuine Bacon-Fat, appointed by me in my last will I give and bequeath: thirty measures of acorns; and to my mother, Mrs. Old-Timer Sow, appointed by me in my last will, I give and bequeath: forty measures of Spartan wheat; and to my sister, Cry-Baby, appointed by me in my last will, whose wedding, alas! I cannot attend, I give and bequeath: thirty measures of barley; and of my nobler parts and property I give and bequeath, to the cobbler, my bristles; to the brawlers, my jaw-bones; to the deaf, my ears; to the shyster lawyers, my tongue; to the cow-herds, my intestines; to the sausage makers, my thighs; to the ladies, my tenderloins; to the boys, my bladder; to the girls, my little pig's tail; to the dancers, my muscles; to the runners and hunters, my <SPAN CLASS="whole">knuckles</SPAN>; to the hired man, my hoofs; and to the cook — though not to be named — I give and bequeath and transmit my belly and appendage which I have dragged with me from the rotten oak bottoms to the pig's sty, for him to tie around his neck and to hang himself with.
"I wish to erect a monument to myself, inscribed with golden letters: 'M. Grunter Corocotta Porker lived <SPAN CLASS="whole">nine-hundred-and-ninety-nine</SPAN> years, and had he lived another half year, a thousand years would have been nearly completed.'
"I ask of you who love me best, you who live like me, I ask you: will not my name remain to be eulogized in all eternity? if you only will prepare my body properly and flavor it well with good condiments, nuts, pepper and honey!
"My master and my relatives, all of you who have witnessed this execution of my last will and testimony, you are requested to sign.
"(Signed) Hard Sausage
Match Maker
Fat Bacon
Celsinus
Meat Ball
Sprout Cabbage."

Thus far the story by Petrus Lambecius. The fifth of the signatories of the Porker's Testimony is Celsinus; and since the other names are fictitious it is quite possible that Lambecius had a special purpose in pointing out the man for whom the dish, Porcellus Celsinianus, — Suckling Pig à la Celsinus — was named.
Celsinus was <INS CLASS="slip"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(SourceErr+'councellor</SPAN>')"
onMouseOut="nd();">counsellor</INS> for Aurelianus, the emperor
	<A CLASS="added_link" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Historia_Augusta/Aurelian/3*.html#44.3
	"TARGET="Historia_Augusta_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EPlusL,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
[<I>Hist. Aug.</I> Aurelian 44.3]</A>.
</DIV>




	<H4 CLASS="start center"><A NAME="377"></A>
377 Roast Pig
	<BR><SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">
Porcellum assum
	</SPAN></H4>

	<P CLASS="justify">
Crush pepper, rue, satury, onions, hard yolks of egg, broth, wine, oil, spices; boil these ingredients, pour over the <SPAN CLASS="outquote">roast</SPAN> pig in the sauce pan and serve.


	<H4 CLASS="start center"><A NAME="378"></A>
378 Pig à la Jardinière
	<BR><SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">
Porcellum hortolanum&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" NAME="378ref1" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#378note1
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">1</A>
	</SPAN></H4>

	<P CLASS="justify">
The pig is boned through the throat and filled with quenelles of chicken forcemeat, finely cut


<A ID="p199"><SPAN CLASS="pagenum"> p199 </SPAN></A><SPAN CLASS="outquote">roast</SPAN> thrushes, fig-peckers, little sausage cakes, made of the pig's meat, Lucanian sausage, stoned dates, edible bulbs <SPAN CLASS="outquote">[glazed onions]</SPAN> snails taken out of the shell <SPAN CLASS="outquote">and poached</SPAN> mallows, leeks, beets, celery, cooked sprouts, coriander, whole pepper, nuts, 15 eggs poured over, broth, which is spiced with pepper, and diluted with 3 eggs; thereupon sew it tight, stiffen, and roast in the oven. When done, open the back <SPAN CLASS="outquote">of the pig</SPAN> and pour over the following sauce: crushed pepper, rue, broth, raisin wine, honey and a little oil, which when boiling is tied with roux.&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" NAME="378ref2" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#378note2
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">2</A>

<DIV CLASS="prose">
	<P>
	<A CLASS="note" NAME="378note1" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#378ref1
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">1</A>
<SPAN CLASS="manuscript">Tor.</SPAN> <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">Hortulanus</SPAN>; Gardener's style, the French equivalent <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">Jardinière</SPAN>, a very common name for all dishes containing young vegetables. However, in the above rich formula there is very little to remind us of the gardener's style, excepting the last part of the formula, enumerating a number of fresh vegetables. It is unthinkable for any gourmet to incorporate these with the rich dressing. The vegetables should be used as a garnish for the finished roast. This leads us to believe that the above is really two distinct formulae, or that the vegetables were intended for garniture.

	<P>
	<A CLASS="note" NAME="378note2" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#378ref2
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">2</A>
This extraordinary and rich dressing, perfectly feasible and admirable when compared with our own "Toulouse," "Financière," "Chipolata," can be palatable only when each component part is cooked separately before being put into the pig. The eggs must be whipped and diluted with broth and poured over the filling to serve as binder. The pig must be parboiled before filling, and the final cooking or roasting must be done very slowly and carefully — procedure not stated by the original which it takes for granted.
</DIV>




	<H4 CLASS="start center"><A NAME="379"></A>
379 Cold Sauce for Boiled Suckling Pig
	<BR><SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">
Jus porro&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" NAME="379ref1" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#379note1
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">1</A> frigidum in porcellum elixum
	</SPAN></H4>

	<P CLASS="justify">
Crush pepper, caraway, dill, little origany, pine nuts, moisten with vinegar, broth,&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" NAME="379ref2" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#379note2
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">2</A> date wine, honey, prepared mustard; sprinkle with a little oil, pepper, and serve.

<DIV CLASS="prose">
	<P>
	<A CLASS="note" NAME="379note1" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#379ref1
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">1</A>
<SPAN CLASS="manuscript">Tor.</SPAN> only; <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">porrò</SPAN> indicating that the sauce may also be served with the foregoing. Wanting in <SPAN CLASS="manuscript">List.</SPAN> <I>et al.</I>

	<P>
	<A CLASS="note" NAME="379note2" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#379ref2
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">2</A>
Wanting in <SPAN CLASS="manuscript">Tor.</SPAN>
</DIV>




	<H4 CLASS="start center"><A NAME="380"></A>
380 Smoked Pig à la Trajanus
	<BR><SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">
Porcellum Traianum&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" NAME="380ref1" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#380note1
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">1</A>
	</SPAN></H4>

	<P CLASS="justify">
Make thus: bone the pig, treat it as for stewing


<A ID="p200"><SPAN CLASS="pagenum"> p200 </SPAN></A>in wine <SPAN CLASS="outquote">℞ No. 375, <I>i.e.</I> marinate for some time in spices, herbs and wine]</SPAN> thereupon hang it in the smoke house&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" NAME="380ref2" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#380note2
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">2</A> next boil it in salt water and serve thus&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" NAME="380ref3" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#380note3
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">3</A> on a large platter.&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" NAME="380ref4" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#380note4
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">4</A>

<DIV CLASS="prose">
	<P>
	<A CLASS="note" NAME="380note1" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#380ref1
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">1</A>
<SPAN CLASS="manuscript">Tor.</SPAN> and <SPAN CLASS="manuscript">Tac.</SPAN> <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">traganum</SPAN>.

	<P>
	<A CLASS="note" NAME="380note2" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#380ref2
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">2</A>
<SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">ad fumum suspendes</SPAN> <SPAN CLASS="manuscript">G.‑V.</SPAN> <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">et adpendeas, et quantum adpendeas, tantum salis in ollam mittes</SPAN> — passage wanting in other texts, meaning, probably, that the more pigs are used for smoking the more salt must be used for pickling which is a matter of course, or, the heavier the pig, . . .

	<P>
	<A CLASS="note" NAME="380note3" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#380ref3
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">3</A>
<SPAN CLASS="manuscript">Tor.</SPAN> <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">atque ita in lance efferes</SPAN>; <SPAN CLASS="manuscript">Tac.</SPAN> <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">&amp; sic eum . . .</SPAN>; <SPAN CLASS="manuscript">G.‑V.</SPAN> <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">et siccum in lance inferes</SPAN>.

	<P>
	<A CLASS="note" NAME="380note4" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#380ref4
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">4</A>
<SPAN CLASS="manuscript">Hum.</SPAN> <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">salso recente</SPAN>, with fresh salt pork. <SPAN CLASS="manuscript">Tor.</SPAN> <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">cum salsamento istoc renecti</SPAN> and <SPAN CLASS="manuscript">Tor.</SPAN> continues without interruption, indicating, perhaps, that the following formula is to be served, or treated (boiled) like the above.
</DIV>




	<H4 CLASS="start center"><A NAME="381"></A>
381 Milk-fed Pig
	<BR><SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">
In porcello lactante&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" NAME="381ref1" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#381note1
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">1</A>
	</SPAN></H4>

	<P CLASS="justify">
One ounce of pepper, a pint of wine, a rather large glass of the best oil, a glass of broth,&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" NAME="381ref2" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#381note2
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">2</A> and rather less than a glass of vinegar.&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" NAME="381ref3" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#381note3
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">3</A>

<DIV CLASS="prose">
	<P>
	<A CLASS="note" NAME="381note1" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#381ref1
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">1</A>
<SPAN CLASS="manuscript">G.‑V.</SPAN> <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">lactans</SPAN>, suckling, milk-fed; other texts: <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">lactente</SPAN>: <SPAN CLASS="manuscript">Dann.</SPAN> wild boar

	<P>
	<A CLASS="note" NAME="381note2" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#381ref2
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">2</A>
wanting in <SPAN CLASS="manuscript">Tac.</SPAN> and <SPAN CLASS="manuscript">Tor.</SPAN>

	<P>
	<A CLASS="note" NAME="381note3" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#381ref3
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">3</A>
a variant of the foregoing, a mild pickling solution for extremely young suckling pigs, prior to their smoking or boiling, or both, which the original does not state.
	<P CLASS="justify">
Schuch and his disciple Danneil, have inserted here seven more pork formulae (<SPAN CLASS="manuscript">Sch.</SPAN> p179, ℞ Nos. 388‑394) taken from the Excerpts of Vinidarius, found at the conclusion of the Apicius formulae.
</DIV>



	<H3 CLASS="center"><A ID="VIII"></A>
VIII
	<BR><SPAN CLASS="smaller">
Hare
	<BR><SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">
Leporem<A CLASS="comment"
onMouseOver="return Ebox('(sic)',WIDTH,60)"
onMouseOut="nd();">º</A>
	</SPAN></SPAN></H3>

	<H4 CLASS="start center"><A NAME="382"></A>
382 Braised Hare
	<BR><SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">
Leporem madidum
	</SPAN></H4>

	<P CLASS="justify">
Is parboiled a little in water, thereupon place it on a roasting pan with oil, to be roasted in the oven. And when properly done, with a change of oil, immerse it in the following gravy: crush pepper, satury, onion, rue, celery seed; moisten with broth, laser, wine, and a little oil. While the roasting <SPAN CLASS="outquote">of the hare</SPAN> is being completed it is several times basted with the gravy.

<DIV CLASS="prose">
	<P>
Wanting in <SPAN CLASS="manuscript">Goll.</SPAN> A difference in the literary style from the foregoing is quite noticeable.
</DIV>




	<H4 CLASS="start center"><A NAME="383"></A>
383 The same, with a Different Dressing
	<BR><SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">
Item alia ad eum impensam
	</SPAN></H4>

	<P CLASS="justify">
<SPAN CLASS="outquote">The hare</SPAN> must be properly kept <SPAN CLASS="outquote">(<I>i.e.</I> aged for a few days after killing)</SPAN>. Crush pepper, dates, laser, raisins, reduced wine, broth and oil; deposit <SPAN CLASS="outquote">the hare in this preparation to be cooked</SPAN> when done, sprinkle with pepper and serve.

<DIV CLASS="prose">
	<P>
Wanting in <SPAN CLASS="manuscript">Goll.</SPAN> <SPAN CLASS="manuscript">Tor.</SPAN> continuing without interruption.
</DIV>




	<H4 CLASS="start center"><A NAME="384"></A>
384 Stuffed Hare
	<BR><SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">
Leporem farsum
	</SPAN></H4>

	<P CLASS="justify">
Whole <SPAN CLASS="outquote">pine</SPAN> nuts, almonds, chopped nuts or beechnuts, whole pepper are mixed with the <SPAN CLASS="outquote">force</SPAN>meat of hare thickened with eggs and wrapped in pig's caul to be roasted in the oven.&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" NAME="384ref1" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#384note1
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">1</A> Another forcemeat is made with rue, plenty of pepper, onion, satury, dates, broth, reduced wine, or spiced wine. This is reduced to the proper consistency and is laid under; but the hare remains in the broth flavored with laser.

<DIV CLASS="prose">
	<P>
	<A CLASS="note" NAME="384note1" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#384ref1
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">1</A>
Reminding of the popular meat loaf, made of remnants: <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">Falscher Hase</SPAN>, "Imitation Hare," as it is known on the Continent.
	<P CLASS="i1 b0 a0 justify">
The ancients probably used the trimmings of hare and other meat for this forcemeat, or meat loaf, either to stuff the hare with, or to make a meal of the preparation itself, as indicated above.
	<P CLASS="i1 b0 a0 justify">
We also recall that the ancients had ingenious baking moulds of metal in the shape of hares and other animals. These moulds, no doubt, were used for baking or the serving of preparations of this sort. the absence of table forks and cutlery as is used today made such preparations very appropriate and convenient in leisurely dining.
</DIV>




	<H4 CLASS="start center"><A NAME="385"></A>
385 White Sauce for Hare
	<BR><SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">
Ius album in assum leporem
	</SPAN></H4>

	<P CLASS="justify">
Pepper, lovage, cumin, celery seed, hard boiled yolks, properly pounded, made into a paste. In a sauce pan boil broth, wine, oil, a little vinegar and chopped onions. While boiling add the paste of spices, stirring with a fagot of origany or satury&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" NAME="385ref1" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#385note1
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">1</A> and when the work is done, bind it with roux.

<DIV CLASS="prose">
	<P>
	<A CLASS="note" NAME="385note1" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#385ref1
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">1</A>
Fagots, or whips made of different herbs and brushes are often employed by Apicius, a very subtle device to impart faint flavors to sauces. the custom


<A ID="p202"><SPAN CLASS="pagenum"> p202 </SPAN></A>has been in use for ages. With the return of mixed drinks in America it was revived by the use of cinnamon sticks with which to stir the drinks.

The above hare formulae are wanting in <SPAN CLASS="manuscript">Goll.</SPAN>
</DIV>




	<H4 CLASS="start center"><A NAME="386"></A>
386 Lights of Hare&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" NAME="386ref1" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#386note1
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">1</A>
	<BR><SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">
Aliter in leporem&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" NAME="386ref2" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#386note2
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">2</A>
	</SPAN></H4>

	<P CLASS="justify">
A fine hash of hare's blood, liver and lungs. Put into a sauce pan broth and oil, and let it boil with finely chopped leeks and coriander; now add the livers and lungs, and, when done, crush pepper, cumin, coriander, laser root, mint, rue, flea-bane, moistened with vinegar.&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" NAME="386ref3" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#386note3
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">3</A>

<DIV CLASS="prose">
	<P>
	<A CLASS="note" NAME="386note1" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#386ref1
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">1</A>
Wanting in <SPAN CLASS="manuscript">Goll.</SPAN>

	<P>
	<A CLASS="note" NAME="386note2" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#386ref2
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">2</A>
<SPAN CLASS="manuscript">Tor.</SPAN> <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">Condimentum ex visceribus leporinis</SPAN>.

	<P>
	<A CLASS="note" NAME="386note3" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#386ref3
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">3</A>
the various texts combine the above and the following formula; but we are of the opinion that they are two distinct preparations.
</DIV>



	<H4 CLASS="start center"><A NAME="387"></A>
387 Lights of Hare, Another Way
	<BR><SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">
Aliter
	</SPAN></H4>

	<P CLASS="justify">
To the hare's liver add the blood and pound it with honey and some of the hare's own gravy; add vinegar to taste and put in a sauce pan, add the lungs chopped fine, make it boil: when done bind with roux, sprinkle with pepper and serve.

<DIV CLASS="prose">
	<P>
This and the preceding formula resemble closely our purées or forcemeats of livers of game and fowl, which are spread on croutons to accompany the roast.
</DIV>




	<H4 CLASS="start center"><A NAME="388"></A>
388 Hare in its own Broth&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" NAME="388ref1" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#388note1
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">1</A>
	<BR><SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">
Aliter leporem ex suo iure
	</SPAN></H4>

	<P CLASS="justify">
Prepare the hare, bone it, garnish&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" NAME="388ref2" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#388note2
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">2</A> put it in a stew pot&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" NAME="388ref3" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#388note3
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">3</A> and when half done add a small bunch of leeks, coriander, dill; while this is being done, put in the mortar pepper, lovage, cumin, coriander seed, laser root, dry onion, mint, rue, celery seed; crush, moisten with broth, add honey, the hare's own gravy, reduced must and vinegar to tate; let it boil, tie with roux, dress, garnish the roast on a platter, underlay the sauce, sprinkle and serve.

<DIV CLASS="prose">
	<P>
	<A CLASS="note" NAME="388note1" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#388ref1
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">1</A>
<I>Cf.</I> <SPAN CLASS="manuscript">Goll.</SPAN> ℞ No. 381.<!-- DON'T LINK, Go ll -->

	<P>
	<A CLASS="note" NAME="388note2" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#388ref2
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">2</A>
with vegetables for braising, possibly larding.

	<P>
	<A CLASS="note" NAME="388note3" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#388ref3
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">3</A>
<SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">braisière</SPAN>, for this is plainly a "potroast" of hare. The boned carcass should


<A ID="p203"><SPAN CLASS="pagenum"> p203 </SPAN></A>be tied; this is perhaps meant by or is included in <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">ornas</SPAN> — garnish, <I>i.e.</I> getting ready for braising.
</DIV>




	<H4 CLASS="start center"><A NAME="389"></A>
389 Hare à la Passenianus&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" NAME="389ref1" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#389note1
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">1</A>
	<BR><SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">
Leporem Passenianum
	</SPAN></H4>

	<P CLASS="justify">
The hare is dressed, boned, the body spread out&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" NAME="389ref2" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#389note2
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">2</A> garnished <SPAN CLASS="outquote">with pickling herbs and spices</SPAN> and hung into the smoke stack.&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" NAME="389ref3" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#389note3
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">3</A> When it has taken on color, cook it half done, wash it, sprinkle with salt and immerse it in wine sauce. In the mortar put pepper, lovage, and crush: moisten with broth, wine and a little oil, heat; when boiling, bind with roux. Now detach the saddle of the roast hare, sprinkle with pepper and serve.

<DIV CLASS="prose">
	<P>
	<A CLASS="note" NAME="389note1" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#389ref1
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">1</A>
This personage, Passenius, or Passenianus, is not identified.

	<P>
	<A CLASS="note" NAME="389note2" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#389ref2
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">2</A>
To bone the carcass, it usually is opened in the back, flattened out and all the bones are easily removed. In that state it is easily <SPAN CLASS="whole">pickled</SPAN> and thoroughly smoked.

	<P>
	<A CLASS="note" NAME="389note3" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#389ref3
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">3</A>
<SPAN CLASS="manuscript">Lan.</SPAN>, <SPAN CLASS="manuscript">Tac.</SPAN>, and <SPAN CLASS="manuscript">Tor.</SPAN> <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">suspendes ad furnum</SPAN>; <SPAN CLASS="manuscript">Hum.</SPAN>, <SPAN CLASS="manuscript">List.</SPAN>, and <SPAN CLASS="manuscript">G.‑V.</SPAN> <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">. . . ad fumum</SPAN>. We accept the latter reading, "in the smoke," assuming that <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">furnum</SPAN> is a typographical error in <SPAN CLASS="manuscript">Lan.</SPAN> and his successors, <SPAN CLASS="manuscript">Tac.</SPAN> and <SPAN CLASS="manuscript">Tor.</SPAN> Still, roasts have for ages been "hung on chains close to or above the open fire"; Torinus may not be wrong, after all, in this essential direction. However, a boned and flattened-out hare would be better broiled on the grill than hung up over the open fire.
</DIV>




	<H4 CLASS="start center"><A NAME="390"></A>
390 Kromeskis of Hare
	<BR><SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">
Leporem isiciatum
	</SPAN></H4>

	<P CLASS="justify">
The hare is cooked and flavored in the same <SPAN CLASS="outquote">above</SPAN> manner; small bits of meat are mixed with soaked nuts; this <SPAN CLASS="outquote">salpicon</SPAN>&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" NAME="390ref1" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#390note1
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">1</A> is wrapped in caul or parchment, the ends being closed by means of skewers <SPAN CLASS="outquote">and fried</SPAN>.

<DIV CLASS="prose">
	<P>
	<A CLASS="note" NAME="390note1" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#390ref1
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">1</A>
We call this preparation a salpicon because it closely resembles to<!-- sic --> our modern salpicons — a fine mince of meats, mushrooms, etc., although the ancient formula fails to state the binder of this mince — either eggs or a thickened sauce, or both.
</DIV>




	<H4 CLASS="start center"><A NAME="391"></A>
391 Stuffed Hare
	<BR><SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">
Leporem farsilem
	</SPAN></H4>

	<P CLASS="justify">
Dress the hare <SPAN CLASS="outquote">as usual</SPAN> garnish <SPAN CLASS="outquote">[marinate]</SPAN> it, place in a square pan.&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" NAME="391ref1" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#391note1
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">1</A> In the mortar put pepper, lovage, origany, moisten with broth, add chicken livers <SPAN CLASS="outquote">sauté</SPAN> cooked brains, finely cut meat&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" NAME="391ref2" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#391note2
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">2</A> 3 <A ID="p204"><SPAN CLASS="pagenum"> p204 </SPAN></A>raw eggs, broth to taste. Wrap it in caul or parchment, fasten with skewers. Half roast on a slow fire. <SPAN CLASS="outquote">Meanwhile</SPAN> put in the mortar pepper, lovage: crush and moisten with broth, wine, season, make it hot, when boiling bind with roux; the half-done hare immerse <SPAN CLASS="outquote">finish cooking in this broth</SPAN> sprinkle with pepper and serve.

<DIV CLASS="prose">
	<P>
	<A CLASS="note" NAME="391note1" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#391ref1
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">1</A>
<SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">Quadratum imponis</SPAN>, which is plain enough. The hare is to be roast therein. <SPAN CLASS="manuscript">Dann.</SPAN> Cut in dice; <SPAN CLASS="manuscript">Goll.</SPAN> Spread it out. <I>Cf.</I> illustration of square roast pan.

	<P>
	<A CLASS="note" NAME="391note2" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#391ref2
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">2</A>
Presumably the trimmings of the hare or of pork. This forcemeat is supposed to be used for the stuffing of the hare; it, being boned, is rolled up, the forcemeat inside, the outside covered with caul or paper, fastened with skewers. Danneil's interpretation suggests the thought that the raw hare's meat is cut into squares which are filled with forcemeat, rolled, wrapped, and roast — a roulade of hare in the regular term.
</DIV>



	<H4 CLASS="start center"><A NAME="392"></A>
392 Boiled Hare
	<BR><SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">
Aliter leporem elixum
	</SPAN></H4>

	<P CLASS="justify">
Dress the hare; <SPAN CLASS="outquote">boil it</SPAN>. In a flat sauce pan pour oil, broth, vinegar, raisin wine, sliced onion, green rue and chopped thyme <SPAN CLASS="outquote">a sauce which is served on the side</SPAN> and so serve it.

<DIV CLASS="prose">
	<P>
<SPAN CLASS="manuscript">Tor.</SPAN> continuing without interruption.
</DIV>




	<H4 CLASS="start center"><A NAME="393"></A>
393 Spiced Sauce for Hare
	<BR><SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">
Leporis conditura
	</SPAN></H4>

	<P CLASS="justify">
Crush pepper, rue, onions, the hare's liver, broth, reduced wine, raisin wine, a little oil; bind with <INS CLASS="slip"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(SourceErr+'rue</SPAN>')"
onMouseOut="nd();">roux</INS> when boiling.

<DIV CLASS="prose">
	<P>
<SPAN CLASS="manuscript">Tor.</SPAN> <I>id.</I>
</DIV>




	<H4 CLASS="start center"><A NAME="394"></A>
394 Sprinkled Hare
	<BR><SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">
Leporem (pipere) sicco sparsum&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" NAME="394ref1" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#394note1
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">1</A>
	</SPAN></H4>

	<P CLASS="justify">
Dress the hare as for kid à la Tarpeius [℞ No. 363]</A>. Before cooking decorate it nicely.&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" NAME="394ref2" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#394note2
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">2</A> Season with pepper, rue, satury, onion, little thyme, moisten with broth, roast in the oven; and all over sprinkle with half an ounce of pepper, rue, onions, satury, 4 dates, and raisins. The gravy is given plenty of color over the open fire, and is seasoned with wine, oil, broth, reduced wine, frequently stirring it <SPAN CLASS="outquote">basting the hare</SPAN> so that it may absorb all the


<A ID="p205"><SPAN CLASS="pagenum"> p205 </SPAN></A>flavor. After that serve it in a round dish with dry pepper.

<DIV CLASS="prose">
	<P>
	<A CLASS="note" NAME="394note1" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#394ref1
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">1</A>
<SPAN CLASS="manuscript">Tac.</SPAN>, <SPAN CLASS="manuscript">Tor.</SPAN> <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">succo sparsum</SPAN>.

	<P>
	<A CLASS="note" NAME="394note2" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#394ref2
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">2</A>
We have no proof that the ancients used the larding needle as we do (or did) in our days. "Decorate" may, therefore, also mean "garnish," <I>i.e.</I> marinate the meat in a generous variety of spices, herbs, roots and wine. It is noteworthy that this term, "garnish," used here and in the preceding formulae has survived in the terminology of the kitchen to this day, in that very sense.
</DIV>




	<H4 CLASS="start center"><A NAME="395"></A>
395 Spiced Hare
	<BR><SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">
Aliter leporem conditum
	</SPAN></H4>

	<P CLASS="justify">
<SPAN CLASS="outquote">The well-prepared hare</SPAN> cook in wine, broth, water, with a little mustard <SPAN CLASS="outquote">seed</SPAN>, dill and leeks with the roots. When all is done, season with pepper, satury, round onions, Damascus plums, wine, broth, reduced wine and a little oil; tie with roux, let boil a little longer <SPAN CLASS="outquote">baste</SPAN> so that the hare is penetrated by the flavor, and serve it on a platter masked with sauce.


	<H3 CLASS="center"><A ID="IX"></A>
IX
	<BR><SPAN CLASS="smaller">
Dormice
	<BR><SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">
Glires
	</SPAN></SPAN></H3>

	<H4 CLASS="start center"><A NAME="396"></A>
396 Stuffed Dormouse&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" NAME="396ref1" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#396note1
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EdNote,WIDTH,180)"
onMouseOut="nd();">1</A>
	<BR><SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">
Glires
	</SPAN></H4>

	<P CLASS="justify">
Is stuffed with a forcemeat of pork and small pieces of dormouse meat trimmings, all pounded with pepper, nuts, laser, broth. Put the dormouse thus stuffed in an earthen casserole, roast it in the oven, or boil it in the stock pot.

<DIV CLASS="prose">
	<P>
	<A CLASS="note" NAME="396note1" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#396ref1
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">1</A>
<SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">Glis</SPAN>, dormouse, a special favorite of the ancients, has nothing to do with mice. The fat dormouse of the South of Europe is the size of a rat, arboreal rodent, living in trees.
	<P CLASS="i1 b0 a0 justify">
Galen, <SPAN CLASS="small">III</SPAN>, <I>de Alim.</I>;
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Pliny_the_Elder/8*.html#223
	"TARGET="Pliny"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Pliny,WIDTH,205)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Plinius, <SPAN CLASS="small">VIII</SPAN>.57/82</A>;
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Varro/de_Re_Rustica/3*.html#2.14
	"TARGET="Varro_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EPlusL,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Varro, <SPAN CLASS="small">III</SPAN></A>, describing the <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">glirarium</SPAN>, place where the dormouse was raised for the table.
	<P CLASS="i1 b0 a0 justify">
Petronius, Cap. 31</A>, describes another way of preparing dormouse. Nonnus, <I>Diaeteticon</I>, p194/5, says that Fulvius&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref:Fulvius_Hirpinus" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#note:Fulvius_Hirpinus
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,MyNote,WIDTH,150)"
onMouseOut="nd();">a</A> Hirpinus was the first man to raise dormouse in the <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">glirarium</SPAN>.&#8203;<A CLASS="ref" ID="ref:glirarium" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#note:glirarium
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,MyNote,WIDTH,150)"
onMouseOut="nd();">b</A>
	<P CLASS="i1 b0 a0 justify">
Dormouse, as an article of diet, should not astonish Americans who relish squirrel, opossum, muskrat, "coon," etc.
</DIV>




	<P CLASS="start center">
End of Book VIII
	<BR>
<SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">Explicit Apicii tetrapus Liber octavus</SPAN> <SPAN CLASS="manuscript">[Tac.]</SPAN>



	<HR CLASS="endnotes"><A ID="endnotes_T"></A>
	<H2>
Thayer's Notes:
	</H2>


	<P CLASS="a0 justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note:Fulvius_Hirpinus" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#ref:Fulvius_Hirpinus
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">a</A>
Vehling writes "Fluvius Hirpinus"; a mistake (repeated in Book <SPAN CLASS="small">VIII</SPAN>) that I'd usually just correct and mark with one of my little bullets,<A CLASS="correction"
onMouseOver="return Ebox('The printed edition<BR>has '+BadF+'Fluvius'+CloseF+'',WIDTH,120)"
onMouseOut="nd();">º</A> were it not that book after book has picked it up and repeated it: poor <SPAN CLASS="whole">scholar</SPAN>&shy;ship doesn't go back to the original. . . .
	<P CLASS="i1 b0 a0 justify">
The man's name was <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">Fulvius</SPAN> or just maybe <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">Flavius</SPAN> (less likely because it only became common much later in Rome's history): both are common man's names and both mean "blond". The word <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">fluvius</SPAN> is not a personal name, and means "river". The manuscripts disagree on his last name; Saglio (Daremberg &amp; Saglio, <I>Dictionnaire des Antiquités Grecques et Romaines</I>,
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/secondary/DARSAG/Glirarium.html
	"TARGET="princeps"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,1,WIDTH,165)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
<I>s.v.</I> Glirarium</A>) gives <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">Lupinus</SPAN> as a possibility; Mayhoff, the editor of Pliny, believes <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">Lippinus</SPAN> to be the correct reading:
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Pliny_the_Elder/9*.html#173
	"TARGET="Pliny"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Pliny,WIDTH,205)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
<I>H. N.</I> <SPAN CLASS="small">IX</SPAN>.173</A>; the man is mentioned again in a similar connection at
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Pliny_the_Elder/8*.html#211
	"TARGET="Pliny"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Pliny,WIDTH,205)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
<SPAN CLASS="small">VIII</SPAN>.211</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note:glirarium" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Apicius/8*.html#ref:glirarium
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">b</A>
For details (and woodcuts) of <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">gliraria</SPAN>, with further citations, see the article
	<A CLASS="smallcaps" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/secondary/DARSAG/Glirarium.html
	"TARGET="princeps"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,1,WIDTH,165)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Glirarium
	</A>
in Daremberg &amp; Saglio's <I>Dictionnaire des Antiquités Grecques et Romaines</I>.



